node.text:
"Real-life stories from the birthing unit - Epidural of the CENTURY.⁠
⁠
It was 9:30pm and I was about finish my shift in the birthing unit. I was handing over things the next midwife when I heard my laboring woman's CTG alarming - this is the machine that monitors the baby's heart rate and uterine contractions.⁠
⁠
I walked back into the room and the woman (who'd had an epidural) was lying on her back happily scrolling through her phone, and her husband was snoring away on the chair next to her.⁠
⁠
I realized the machine was alarming as it'd lost contact with the baby's heart rate. This is quite common, and most of the time it's just positional as the baby moves down the pelvis.⁠
⁠
I was about to move the woman and help her onto her side, but as I pulled back the sheet, I got the shock of my life when I saw a healthy baby boy laying there all cozy between his mother's legs. 😳😲⁠
⁠
Mum had absolutely NO idea that she'd given birth, and Dad got a huge surprise when he awoke.⁠
⁠
The night-shift midwife, who'd been working for 40 years, had never seen this happen before!⁠
⁠
So...here's to the anesthetist. 🍸 She definitely deserves the best epidural of the year (or century) award!"⁠

.⁠
Image and story via @makelabourhappen ❤️

node.text:
For this child we have prayed.
God answered our prayer through adoption. 

Edited: to answer a specific question we keep on getting in the comments.

We didn’t ask for a baby of a specific colour, race or culture. We saw a need and stepped up. We applied for adoption and was educated on the need in our country. It breaks my heart to think that people will rather leave a child in a gutter (yes, in a gutter, babies get abandoned daily in our country- in gutters, toilets, open fields) than adopt a child of color. How could humanity have harden their hearts so much? 

Poverty is at an all time high and still - people choose to focus on color. Children DIE - still people choose to see color. 

Please understand me - I see color too, but I choose to celebrate our differences, I choose to see harmony (a beautiful blending) I choose to show the world that we do not have to divide because of our race or colour, I choose to show that love is colorblind. @d.niel_sa

node.text:
"Its now been two years since I’ve nursed a babe.⁣
⁣
Two years since I felt the tingling sensation of my milk letting down.⁣
⁣
Two years since I’ve stroked a babes cheek while they look up at me, milk drunk and sated.⁣
⁣
Two years since my body has been essential to their life.⁣
⁣
To think I used to feel SHAME.⁣
⁣
To think I ever felt like a failure.⁣
⁣
When now I sit here, desperate for that feeling again.⁣
⁣
Desperate.
⁣
I had two breastfeeding journeys in my lifetime—neither was a bit like the other. ⁣
⁣
Im grateful for every moment that we made it.⁣
⁣
Every tear that we shed.⁣
⁣
This is one of the first photos ever taken of myself nursing the girls (shared a few more in my stories). ⁣
⁣
It actually took 8 days for my milk to come in so what we did was, dry nursing on the nipple off and on, followed by a tube system that filled a nipple shield with formula to simulate nursing. ⁣
⁣
It was a rigorous process that required my husbands help.⁣
⁣
Every. Single. Time. ⁣
⁣
So every 2 hours like clockwork we would start the process over - for eight days straight. ⁣
⁣
Nothings ever made me feel so lost, yet so proud.⁣
⁣
There is truly nothing in the world like it. ⁣
⁣
You know I kept a bag of breast milk in the freezer for almost a year after I stopped nursing.⁣
⁣
It’s taken a long time to grieve the end of that journey.⁣
And I’m still somewhere in it.⁣
Closer to the top now.⁣
⁣
Closer to closure."

📷: @th3littlestavenger

node.text:
"You guys...it worked! It actually worked! I’m still in absolute shock. Kevin hasn’t stopped smiling since we found out and I’ve been in disbelief ever since. But we’re pregnant! Like legit pregnant. There’s a baby growing inside of me. A baby Kevin and I have prayed for and fought for every single day since our wedding day. That’s 1,672 days to be exact.
⁣
I’ve dreamed of this day for a long time and I honestly started losing hope that it would ever come. There are just no words to describe it. And although it’s incredibly exciting for us, my heart aches so much for those who haven’t had success yet. I know how much these posts can hurt because I’ve been on the receiving end of that hurt for over four years. So just know, you’re on my mind and I’m always rooting for you.
⁣
A huge thank you to (viosfertility) (ellenhayesmd) and all the staff at (viosfertilitymke) for never giving up on us. Our journey hasn’t been easy and your compassion and care has always been comforting.
⁣
Thank you so very much to everyone who prayed for us, supported us and sent an endless amount of love our way. I’m convinced that’s what helped us finally get pregnant. Kevin and I feel so blessed to have you all with us on this journey and your kind words are always appreciated. 
⁣
I will give another update post in the next day or so giving all 3 beta numbers, how far along we are and what else we know. I also eventually want to have a conversation about what my page will look like going forward."❤️❤️👼
